Here in Boston we have been living through several consecutive record-breaking snowfalls.  At my house, we have received six feet of snow (nearly two meters) over the past two weeks, and we have more on the way.  In just 14 days, we have set the record for most snowfall in a 30-day and 40-day period, and we are already at almost double the annual average, and it's only mid-February.  Schools, government services, and public transportation have been shut down repeatedly, and the entire city has come to a virtual halt for a couple days on two separate occasions, with a full travel ban in place for all vehicles.  In short, this has been a crazy past couple of weeks.

But with the craziness comes beauty, as our normal bleak winter landscape has been transformed into an arctic wonderland where, when the wind settles down, peace and softness seem to cloak everything around.  This is the brook behind our house, in the midst of one such lull, while the snow was falling steadily, and all the world seemed still and quiet.

Thanks very much for stopping by, and I hope that wherever you are, peace and quiet are winning out over the sound and fury that so often bring so much to ruin.

I blew them off the best I could with a rocket blower while the image was exposing, and then cleaned with a brush and lens cloth in between exposures. title._content: Golden Age of LP Records - Where to Buy LPs in Boston in the 1960s / 1970s.

description._content:
The back of the November 1969 Schwann catalog had an ad for the Harvard Cooperative Society (Coop) stores. The Palmer Street Annex, one block from Harvard Square, had the best selection of records in Boston. They would bet big on new artists displaying huge piles of records stacked on the floor, before anyone knew they were going to be stars - Bruce Springsteen and Jimi Hendrix for example. Prices were also very good. Several other record stores near Harvard Square featured bootleg, imported, and out of print records - some not in the Schwann Catalog.

The day after finals ended in my senior year I went to the Harvard Coop with a friend. He was a foreign student on a full scholarship from his home country and noticed that the receipt for records was identical to the receipt for books - he went on a record buying binge and sent the bill to the embassy (they paid it without question). Neither of us actually graduated after 4 years and we both lived very near Harvard Square for the next 2 years. - record buying continued to interfere with my studies.

(I DID NOT attend Harvard!!!)

description._content:
Blue skies and winter wonderland conditions in a brief break between a couple of Boston's several recent, successive, big blizzards.  We got over nine feet of snow (nearly three meters) this year, setting a new all-time record.  And virtually all of this came in just over a month, beginning in the last few days of January.  This woodland scene, which looks as if it could be high in the Rockies or deep in the Black Forest somewhere, is actually just a couple of minutes' walk from a station on Boston's Orange Line subway.

This is iPhoneography.

title._content: Early 20th Century Art Deco Architecture in Boston Historic District of Aberdeen in Brighton Neighborhood, Daytime Long Exposure

description._content: Buy a print or commercial license: www.gregdubois.com/Galleries/Boston/Boston-Architecture/i... Find me on instagram @greg_dubois instagram.com/greg_dubois/ This is my favorite building in my neighborhood and I think is the centerpiece of what is known as the Aberdeen Historic District of Boston. I have posted a couple different angles before, but I have always wanted to nail a front on facade, tried a couple times over the years. There were perfect clouds last weekend while a storm was clearing out, so I took advantage and went right to this building for unfinished business, and I figured the historic snow levels would help me get this facade without cars in the frame. There was a benefit from a huge snow bank that went well into the street, as I was able to set up on the bank and get an angle that normally I would have to set up well into the street for. It was really tough, I had to wait out a few delivery people that parked directly in front of the building and a couple people unloading groceries etc. Between that and waiting for the right clouds it took me well over an hour to get this image, luckily I got this single exposure with great clouds and no cars before the clouds disappeared. title._content: Green Tide Pool on Seaside Cliff with North Atlantic Ocean Horizon, Nahant Massachusetts USA

description._content: Buy a print or commercial license: www.gregdubois.com/Galleries/Travel/North-Shore-Massachus... Find me on instagram @greg_dubois instagram.com/greg_dubois/ This was a completely recreational shot. We were down enjoying the sea cliffs on the best Sunday in months, sunny and warm. This was a nice flat spot on the cliff and there was a green tide pool, so it was a no brainer. This is a single image straight out of the camera just with punched up color. A 90 deg angle was perfect for my 100 x 100mm circular polarizer, so I was able to stack a grad ND with only the depth of the standard LEE holder. This allowed me to shoot through three filters at 16mm with barely any vignetting, and I have found that the square circular polarizer typically always works the best at 90 degree rotations anyways. description._content: Buy a print or commercial license: www.gregdubois.com/Galleries/Boston/Boston-Architecture/i... Find me on instagram @greg_dubois instagram.com/greg_dubois/ I've been watching them build this modern residential tower in East Cambridge on my drives over the Leverett Circle Connector Bridge. Took a walk around the building and decided to go front on with the entrance. Someone from the building came out and asked me what I was doing, once I explained what I was doing they let it ride and I was able to hang out until the best batch of clouds came through. title._content: Foggy Golden Sunrise over Boston Skyline, Beacon Hill, Massachusetts State House, and Charles River Reflection - Cambridge MA USA

description._content: Buy a print or commercial license: www.gregdubois.com/Galleries/Boston/Boston-Skyline-and-Br... Find me on instagram @greg_dubois instagram.com/greg_dubois/ It was really foggy yesterday morning, so on my way out of town I decided to take Memorial Drive and assess the situation on the Charles. I couldn't even see the Prudential or the Hancock, so that ruled out any Back Bay angles. I ventured down the sidewalk and noticed some intense coloring around downtown and Beacon Hill as the sun broke through the fog. So I scrambled for position and got out the telephoto. For about 10 minutes there was incredible swirling fog and golden light for this angle, and I got 5 frames of varying focal lengths. This was the first frame I took and was the widest. Canon 6d Canon 70-200mm f/4L at 94 LEE Big Stopper (3.0ND) f/20, ISO 50, 120 sec

title._content: Boston Skyline and Charles River Dragon Boats, Cloudy Sunrise over Back Bay and Harvard Bridge with Mirror Reflection from Cambridge MA USA

description._content: Buy a print or commercial license www.gregdubois.com/Galleries/Boston/Boston-Skyline-and-Br... Find me on instagram @greg_dubois instagram.com/greg_dubois/ I have shot this place a handful of times in the past couple of years. I took a different approach on this one to get some sharper boats and cloud detail. The river was super calm and there was no wind, so it was optimal conditions to get a different take of this subject. I shot with a wide aperture to get a short exposure length, just enough to get the right amount of water blur. Probably due to my lens, there was absolutely no quality loss in sharpness at this wider aperture, and I think it might even look better than stopped down further. I took around 30 frames while the light was perfect, but it soon clouded over. Canon 6d 16-35 f/2.8L II at 27 LEE Little Stopper (1.8 ND) LEE 0.9 Hard GND f/5.6, ISO 100, 5.4 sec
